@node Introduction

  @{b}- Introduction -@{ub}

FileChecker is a program which allows the user to identify various types of
files in a quick and easy way by using a GUI. In addition it can add the
correct extension to files that are missing or have a wrong extension in the
file name. It can't be used for viewing any files since it is intended for
recognizing file types only.

The current version of FileChecker is able to identify over 45 different file
formats, this includes standard types like IFF, GIF, PNG, JPEG, BMP, AIFF,
WAV, MP3, MPEG, AVI and Quicktime. FileChecker will also recognize some of
the more "exotic" formats like PBM, PGM and PPM.



   @{b}- Why I made it -@{ub}

FileChecker is a program that I had been thinking about making for a long
time, the main reason for this was that I wanted to copy all the pictures I
have made on my Amiga over the years over to my PC. But there was one little
problem: when I gave the pictures their names back then, I did not include
an extension in the file name. An example of this is that I once called a
picture I had made "HeavyMetal" instead of "HeavyMetal.IFF".

This would lead to problems because of the rather primitive file recognition
method that is used by Windows (where files only is recognized by checking
the extension in the file name). I could have added the extensions by renaming
all files manually, but this sounded like too much work for me.
So I created the very first version of FileChecker, this was done in only one
evening because I re-used various parts of some of my other projects. In the
following day I added the correct extensions to all my picture files.

The first version of FileChecker was very simple and it supported only a
couple of picture formats, it also had a rather primitive looking GUI, but
it was good enough for me since it did exactly the job I created it for.
I did not have any plans of distributing it back then since it was only
intended for my own personal use, but later I decided to develop it further
and I added support for more file formats. I also did some changes to the
GUI (by adding some more gadgets and cleaning it up a little).

And the result is version 1.0 of FileChecker, I hope you like it.

@endnode

