@node Requirements

  @{b}- Requirements -@{ub}

FileChecker requires an Amiga with OS 3.0 or higher (it is only tested with
OS 3.9). In addition it requires two files - Gui and Gui4Cli, both of them
are included in this distribution.
The two files can be in the same drawer as FileChecker, but it is recommended
that you either move or copy them to C:.

@endnode


@node Installation

  @{b}- Installation -@{ub}

This is easy! Just copy Gui & Gui4Cli to C:, then copy FileChecker to where
ever you want on your harddisk.

@endnode




@node FileCheckerUsage "FileChecker Usage"

                   @{b}---++-  FileChecker 1.0  -++---@{ub}

                         @{b}     U s a g e     @{ub}



  @{b}- The Listview -@{ub}
Here you can select the files that you want to be checked, just select the
ones that you want to identify and press the "Start" button to begin.

Please note that selected directories will be totally ignored, files that
are present in them will not be checked. This is done for safety reasons
for when the "Add Extensions" option is enabled. 


  @{b}- Start -@{ub}
When you press this button, FileChecker will try to identify the files that
you have selected in the listview. If a file is correctly identified, the
extension in the file name will be checked, and if this is either wrong or
missing, you will be notified about it.

If the extension was wrong/missing and the "Add Extensions" option is enabled,
FileChecker will automatically add the correct extension to the file name.
You don't have to worry about the icon (if the file has one) since it will
be renamed too.

The result of all this will appear in a output window. For more details about
this, check out the @{"Output Window" link OutputWindow} section.


  @{b}- Add Extensions -@{ub}
If you enable this option, FileChecker will add the correct extension to the
file-name of files that either have a wrong or missing extension.


  @{b}- Upper Case -@{ub}
If enabled, the extensions that are added to file names will be in upper case
instead of lower case.


  @{b}- Hide Icons -@{ub}
This will hide the icons in the directory listview. 


I will not bother with explaining the Volumes, Parent & Quit buttons since I'm
sure that you already understand what they will do :-)

@endnode


@node FileCheckerMenu "FileChecker Menu"

                   @{b}---++-  FileChecker 1.0  -++---@{ub}

                          @{b}     M e n u     @{ub}



  @{b}- About File Checker -@{ub}
This menu item will show you some information about FileChecker.


  @{b}- Preview file -@{ub}
If you select this menu item, FileChecker will read the first 1024 bytes of
the first selected file in the listview, this will then be viewed as text in
a window that will open on your screen. This can be useful if you want to
inspect files for finding out about the file-headers for example.
It is possible to have several windows open at the same time.

Please note that FileChecker can't read character 0 (the NULL char, not the
number itself), instead it will be read as character 1 (Start Of Heading).
This is all due to an limitation in Gui4Cli. It is nothing important really,
but I just thought that I should mention it anyway.


  @{b}- Rename file(s) -@{ub}
This allows you to rename the files that you have selected in the listview.
There is one thing that you must have in mind: If you have the "Hide Icons"
option ON, the icons of files that you rename will automatically be renamed
too, but if you set this option OFF, you will have to rename the icons
manually yourself.


I will not bother with explaining the Iconify & Quit menu items since I'm
sure that you already understand what they will do :-)

@endnode



@node Important

  @{b}- Important -@{ub}

Before using FileChecker, please take your time and note the following:


  @{b}-  I  -@{ub}
File types is only recognized by reading the file header (the first part of
the file), the extension in the file name is totally ignored. I have decided
to do things this way because I want FileChecker to be as accurate as possible.


  @{b}-  II  -@{ub}
When you want FileChecker to add correct extensions to files which have either
a wrong or missing extension, have in mind that this will actually rename the
files. This may not always be such a good idea since the files might be in use
by programs or other tasks. Be careful about what files you let FileChecker
process and don't use it blindly on every file you come across.


  @{b}-  III  -@{ub}
Have in mind that FileChecker may sometimes wrongly identify files, this can
especially happen with RAW files (files that are saved without a standard
header). Here is an example of this: I once used FileChecker to check some raw
samples I have stored on my Amiga, the majority of them was correctly reported
as unknown but one of them was wrongly identified as a TIFF picture.
The moral has to be: Don't always trust blindly everything FileChecker reports
and use some common sense when you are checking files.


  @{b}-  IV  -@{ub}
FileChecker will never check files that are present in directories selected
in the listview, there is no harm in selecting dirs though, they will simply
be ignored. This is done for safety reasons when the "Add Extensions" option
is enabled.


  @{b}-  V  -@{ub}
MP3 files are supported in FileChecker, but don't be surprised if you ever
come across some MP3 files which is not recognized by FileChecker. The reason
for this is that there are a lot of various headers in use for the MP3 format
out there. Personally I have come across over twenty different MP3 headers by
now. The same thing might also be true with other file formats like HTML, RTF,
TIFF, MPEG and QuickTime.


  @{b}-  VI  -@{ub}
PowerPacked files will always be counted as such, this is regardless of what
the file format really is. If you have the "Add Extensions" option enabled,
the ".pp" extension will always be added to the file name (the exception is
of course if the file already has a ".pp" extension :-) .


  @{b}-  VII  -@{ub}
FileChecker will never replace extensions in file names, a new extension will
always be added to the existing name instead. Here is an example: imagine that
you have a PNG file called "GWAR.iff". When you use FileChecker to check the
file, it will be renamed to "GWAR.iff.png" instead of "GWAR.png".
There is a good reason why extensions never are replaced, it is because the
extension will always be counted as whatever follows the last dot in the file
name. If a file is called "3.14", ".14" will be counted as the extension.

There has never really been a tradition in the Amiga world to use extensions
in file names (well, at least not in the earliest years), and as a result of
this, there has almost never been any Amiga programs that will automatically
add an extension to the file name when a new file is saved.
This leads to the fact that there are probably many files out there which
lacks an extension in their names, so I have decided to let FileChecker only
add and never replace extensions in order to avoid possible conflicts when
dots are used in the file names.

@endnode



@node StartingFileChecker "Starting FileChecker"

  @{b}- Starting FileChecker -@{ub}

This section describes how to start FileChecker.

  @{b}- Starting from Workbench -@{ub}
Just double-click the FileChecker icon. Remember that if you change the icon
to another one, the Default Tool of the new icon MUST be set to "Gui".


  @{b}- Starting from Shell -@{ub}
You can start FileChecker in a Shell by typing "Gui FileChecker". This has one
limitation, you can't give the name of a file or dir as an argument, in other
words, typing "Gui FileChecker Ram:Naughty.iff" is not possible.

@endnode



@node OutputWindow "The Output Window"

   @{b}- The Output Window -@{ub}

This section describes the output FileChecker makes when checking files.

While FileChecker is processing the selected files, you will be notified
about the result of this in a output window. The text in this window will
include the file names which might appear in different colors:


If a file is recognized and it has a correct extension in the file name,
the text will be in black.

If a file is recognized but the extension is wrong or missing, the text will
appear in white. If you have the "Add Extensions" option enabled, the file
will be given the correct extension and the new name of the file will be
printed below the original line.

For unrecognized or empty files the text will be in blue.





@endnode


@node FileTypes "File Types List"

   @{b}- File Types List -@{ub}

Here is a list over the file types that the current version of
FileChecker will recognize:


     @{b}File Type               Extension(s)@{ub}

     AmigaGuide file:        .GUIDE
     HTML document:          .HTML  .HTM   .HTT   .HTTP
     PDF document:           .PDF

     Amiga Icon:             .INFO
     IFF  picture:           .IFF   .ILBM
     IFF DEEP pic:           .DIP
     GIF  picture:           .GIF
     JPEG picture:           .JPG   .JPEG
  *  JPEG 2000 pic:          .JP2
     PNG  picture:           .PNG
     BMP  picture:           .BMP
  *  PBM  picture:           .PBM   .PNM
  *  PGM  picture:           .PGM   .PNM   .PBM
  *  PPM  picture:           .PPM   .PNM   .PBM
  *  TIFF picture:           .TIFF  .TIF   .SEP
  *  SUN RASTER pic:         .RAS
  *  Rendition pic:          .6RN
     TVPaint project:        .PRO

     Animation file:         .ANIM
     QuickTime video:        .MOV   .QT    .MV
     AVI  video:             .AVI
     MPEG video:             .MPG   .MPEG

     MP3 audio:              .MP3   .MP2
     MIDI file:              .MID

     MED module:             .MED   .MMD
     XM  module:             .XM
     DBM module:             .DBM
     S3M module:             .S3M   .STM
     MOD module:             .MOD

     8SVX sample:            .8SVX  .8SV   .SND   .IFF
     16VX sample:            .16VX  .SND   .IFF
     AIFF sample:            .AIFF  .AIF
     WAV  sample:            .WAV

     PowerPacked file:       .PP
     LhA archive:            .LHA   .LZH
     LZX archive:            .LZX
     Zoo archive:            .ZOO
     Zip archive:            .ZIP
     GZip archive:           .GZ

     Wordworth doc:          .DOC
     Word document:          .DOC
  *  RTF  document:          .RTF
  *  WordPerfect doc:        .DOC

     Amiga prg/data
     Gui4Cli program
     Text File


  * = Tested on a few files only.



Please note the following:

Some file types uses more than one extension, FileChecker will accept all of
these to be correct, but when adding extensions to file names, only the first
one in the list will be used. Here is an example:
With HTML files, FileChecker will accept both .HTML, .HTM, .HTT and .HTTP to
be correct extensions, but FileChecker will only use the .HTML extension when
adding extensions to this type of files.

I'm not entirely sure if the extensions listed are correct for all file types,
and as an example I can take 8SVX & 16VX samples, I don't know if using the
.IFF extension is considered to be acceptable on these types of files.
Another thing is music modules, I'm not sure if the extensions used on them
are correct. If you come across something that is wrong, please let @{"me" link Author} know
about it.   

FileChecker will never add any extensions to Amiga program/data files, Gui4Cli
program files or pure Text files.

@endnode


@node PrgInformasjon "Program Information"

   @{b}- Program Information -@{ub}

FileChecker was made by using D. Keletsekis's Gui4Cli 3.8.
Gui4Cli is an easy scripted language for creating & running GUIs.
If you want to get hold of the whole package for making your own ones,
it can be found :

  - on AmiNet, under Dev/Gui/Gui4Cli.lha, or 
  - at D. Keletsekis's web page, http://users.hol.gr/~dck/gcmain.htm


@endnode


